backgrounds:
Fact: We construct a symmetric meromorphic function $M(s,t)$ of two complex variables $(s,t)$
with a third variable $u$ constrained by
\begin{equation}
s+t+u=\sigma,\qquad \sigma>0\ \text{fixed}.
\label{eq:stu_sum}
\end{equation}
The amplitude is a sum of (i) a crossing-symmetric ``dispersive'' (pole) piece and (ii) an
a priori ambiguous crossing-symmetric polynomial ``contact'' piece.
Definition (crossing action): Define $u=\sigma-s-t$. Crossing symmetry means invariance under any permutation of $(s,t,u)$.
In this benchmark, we enforce it by constructing $M$ as a sum over the cyclic channels.
Definition (pole kernel): Fix a finite set of real pole locations
\[
\mathcal{A}=\{a_1,a_2,\dots,a_N\}\subset \mathbb{R},\qquad a_i\neq a_j.
\]
Define the kernel
\begin{equation}
K_a(x)\equiv \frac{x^4}{x-a},
\label{eq:kernel}
\end{equation}
and define the ``dispersive'' part
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{D}(s,t)\equiv \sum_{a\in\mathcal{A}}\Big(K_a(s)+K_a(t)+K_a(u)\Big).
\label{eq:D_def}
\end{equation}
Definition (contact polynomial ansatz): Define the symmetric polynomials (subject to \eqref{eq:stu_sum})
\begin{equation}
S_2 \equiv s^2+t^2+u^2,\qquad S_3\equiv s^3+t^3+u^3.
\end{equation}
Consider the contact-term ansatz
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}(s,t)\equiv c_0+c_2\,S_2+c_3\,S_3,
\label{eq:P_def}
\end{equation}
and define the full crossing-symmetric amplitude
\begin{equation}
M(s,t)\equiv \mathcal{D}(s,t)+\mathcal{P}(s,t).
\label{eq:M_def}
\end{equation}
Definition (subtracted amplitude and locality constraint): Define the $t$-subtracted amplitude
\begin{equation}
\widehat M(s,t)\equiv M(s,t)-\sum_{a\in\mathcal{A}}K_a(t)
= \sum_{a\in\mathcal{A}}\big(K_a(s)+K_a(u)\big)+\mathcal{P}(s,t).
\label{eq:Mhat_def}
\end{equation}
\emph{Locality constraint:} for each fixed $t$ (with $\sigma$ fixed),
\begin{equation}
\widehat M(s,t)=O\!\left(\frac{1}{s}\right)\qquad\text{as }s\to\infty.
\label{eq:locality}
\end{equation}
Equivalently: the coefficients of $s^2$ and $s^1$ in the large-$s$ expansion of $\widehat M(s,t)$ vanish.
Notation (pole sums): Let
\[
N\equiv |\mathcal{A}|,\qquad A_1\equiv \sum_{a\in\mathcal{A}} a.
\]

