Setup: In the following, SRE refers to stabilizer R\'enyi entropy, $\alpha$ denotes the R\'enyi index, BCCO refers to boundary condition changing operator, and is denoted by $\mathcal{B}_{2\alpha}(x)$.
$\Delta_{2\alpha}$ denotes the scaling dimension of $\mathcal{B}_{2\alpha}(x)$.
The goal is to establish the scaling behavior of the mutual SRE.
We consider the case where $AB$ forms the entire quantum system $\psi$, with subsystems defined as $A = \{1, 2, \ldots, l\}$ and $B = \{l+1,l+2, \ldots, L\}$.
Let $l_c = (L/\pi) \sin(\pi l/L)$.
We use $\ket{\psi}$ to denote an $L$-qubit pure state.
Definition (Pauli matrices): Pauli matrices are labeled as
\begin{align}\label{eq:paulimatrix}
\sigma^{00} & =\mqty(1  & 0 \\0&1) ,& \sigma^{10} &= \mqty(0&1\\1&0),\notag\\
\sigma^{01} & = \mqty(1 & 0 \\0&-1),& \sigma^{11} &=\mqty(0&-i\\i&0).
\end{align}
Definition ($\psi$): Here, $\psi=\ketbra{\psi}{\psi}$ represents the density matrix corresponding to $\ket{\psi}$.
Definition ($\sigma^{\vec{m}}$): The $L$-qubit Pauli string $\sigma^{\vec{m}}$ is given by
\begin{equation}\label{eq:paulistring}
\sigma^{\vec{m}} = \bigotimes_{j=1}^{L} \sigma^{m_{2j-1}m_{2j}}\quad(\vec{m}\in\qty{0,1}^{2L}),
\end{equation}
Definition ($\alpha$-SRE): the $\alpha$-SRE is defined as follows:
\begin{equation}
M_{\alpha}(\psi) = \frac{1}{1-\alpha} \ln\sum_{\vec{m}}\frac{\Tr^{2\alpha}[\sigma^{\vec{m}}\psi]}{2^L}.
\end{equation}
Definition (Mutual SRE): \begin{equation}
W_{\alpha}(l) =  M_\alpha(\rho_A) + M_\alpha(\rho_B) - M_\alpha(\rho_{AB})
\end{equation}
Definition (Choi-Jamiolkowski isomorphism): $\ket*{\mathrm{vec}(\cdot)}$ is a linear map defined as $\ket*{\mathrm{vec}(\ketbra{x}{y})}=\ket{x}\!\ket{y}$ in the computational basis, which establishes the Choi-Jamiolkowski isomorphism between operators and states in the doubled Hilbert space.
Definition (Bell basis): We define the Bell basis as
\begin{equation}
\ket*{\mathrm{Bell}^{b_1b_2}}=\frac{\ket*{0b_1}+(-1)^{b_2}\ket{1\bar{b}_1}}{\sqrt{2}},
\end{equation}
Definition ($P^{\vec{m}}$): $P^{\vec{m}}=2^{-L}\ketbra{\mathrm{vec}(\sigma^{\vec{m}})}{\mathrm{vec}(\sigma^{\vec{m}})}$.
Definition (Participation): $p_{\vec{m}} := \Tr[P^{\vec{m}}(\psi\otimes\psi^\ast)]$ is the participation in the Bell basis, or equivalently, the Born probability associated with the Bell-state measurements performed on the doubled state.

Definition (Sum rule): From the dispersion relation, the low-energy two-to-two scattering amplitude has the following expansion
\begin{align}
B_{ijkl}(s,t) & =  \sum_{n\geq 0}c_{ijkl}^{0,n}t^n + \sum_{n\geq 0}c_{ijkl}^{1,n}v t^n  + \sum_{m\geq 2}\sum_{n\geq 0} c_{ijkl}^{m,n} v^m t^n \,.
\end{align}
where $v\equiv s+\frac{t}{2}$, and $s,t$ are the Mandelstam variables, and $i,j,k,l$ are the quantum numbers for the incoming and outgoing particles. For $m\geq2$, the $c_{ijkl}^{m,n}$ has the following sum rule
\begin{align}
c_{ijkl}^{m,n} & = \Bigg\langle  \big[\rho_\ell^{ijkl}(\mu) + (-1)^m \rho_\ell^{ilkj}(\mu) \big]\sum_{p=0}^{n}\frac{L_\ell^p H_{m+1}^{n-p}}{\mu^{m+n+1}} \Bigg\rangle\,,
\end{align}
where $\rho^{ijkl}_\ell(\mu)$ is called the spectral density, and
\begin{align}
&~~~~~~~~~~~~\Big\langle\,...\,\Big\rangle \equiv \sum_\ell 16(2\ell+1) \int_{\Lambda^2}^{\infty} d\mu\Big(\,...\,\Big),
\\
L_\ell^n&\equiv\frac{\Gamma(\ell+n+1)}{n!\Gamma(\ell-n+1)\Gamma(n+1)},~~
H_{m+1}^q \equiv\frac{\Gamma(m+q+1)}{(-2)^q\Gamma(q+1)\Gamma(m+1)},
\end{align}
while for $0\leq m\leq 1$ there is no such relation.
Definition (Crossing symmetry): The amplitude $B_{ijkl}(s,t)$ has the crossing symmetry for the massless case
\begin{equation}
B_{ijkl}(s,t)=B_{ikjl}(t,s),\quad B_{ijkl}(s,t)=B_{ilkj}(-s-t,t)
\end{equation}

