backgrounds:
Definition (comoving momentum variable): Assume a radiation era with $T\propto a^{-1}$. Define the dimensionless comoving momentum
\[
q \equiv \frac{p}{T}.
\]
For free streaming ($C[f]=0$), $q$ is conserved along trajectories, so the Liouville operator reduces to a partial derivative
in the evolution variable below.
Definition (evolution variable): Let $x\equiv m/T$ for some fixed reference mass $m$ (any monotonic variable in $T$ would work).
We study an isotropic phase-space distribution $f(q,x)$ on $q\in[0,\infty)$.
Definition (moments that matter): Define the moments
\begin{equation}\label{eq:moments}
Y_n(x)\equiv \int_0^\infty q^n f(q,x)\,dq,\qquad n=2,3,4.
\end{equation}
(These are the only moments we will ever use.)
The \emph{mean comoving momentum} and a proxy for the \emph{width} are
\begin{equation}\label{eq:mean_var}
\bar q(x)\equiv \frac{Y_3(x)}{Y_2(x)},\qquad
\mathrm{Var}_q(x)\equiv \frac{Y_4(x)}{Y_2(x)}-\left(\frac{Y_3(x)}{Y_2(x)}\right)^2.
\end{equation}
Definition (source: freeze-in injection at a fixed comoving momentum): We model production by a source term that injects particles at fixed $q=q_0>0$:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:source}
S(q,x)=\mathcal{S}(x)\,\delta(q-q_0),\qquad \mathcal{S}(x)\ge 0.
\end{equation}
We will use a simple ``one-step'' source in the examples:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:S1}
\mathcal{S}(x)=A\,x^3 e^{-x},\qquad A>0,
\end{equation}
and in the final question we will switch to a two-step source.
Definition (collision operator: relaxation-time kineticization that conserves number): We approximate elastic scattering with the bath by a relaxation term
\begin{equation}\label{eq:collision}
C_{\rm el}[f](q,x)=\gamma(x)\big(f_{\rm eq}(q;x)-f(q,x)\big),
\qquad \gamma(x)\ge 0,
\end{equation}
where the target (kinetic-equilibrium) shape is Maxwell--Boltzmann in $q$:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:feq}
f_{\rm eq}(q;x)=\mathcal{N}(x)\,e^{-q}.
\end{equation}
The normalization $\mathcal{N}(x)$ is chosen to enforce \emph{number conservation by elastic scattering}:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:number_conservation_condition}
\int_0^\infty q^2\,C_{\rm el}[f](q,x)\,dq=0.
\end{equation}
Definition (Boltzmann equation): The phase-space Boltzmann equation in this toy model is
\begin{equation}\label{eq:boltzmann_f}
\partial_x f(q,x)= S(q,x) + C_{\rm el}[f](q,x),
\qquad f(q,0)=0.
\end{equation}

