Definition (Density matrix): The density matrix for a two-qubit system $\mathcal{AB}$ has the following decomposition
\begin{align}
\rho_{\mathcal{A}\mathcal{B}}= \frac{1}{4}\big(\mathbb{I}_4
+ P_\mathcal{A}^i  (\sigma^i \!\otimes\! \mathbb{I}_2)
+ P_\mathcal{B}^i  (\mathbb{I}_2 \!\otimes\! \sigma^i)
+ C_{\mathcal{A}\mathcal{B}}^{ij} (\sigma^i \!\otimes\! \sigma^j) \big) \notag
\end{align}
where $P_\mathcal{A/B}$ is the polarization vector for system $\mathcal{A/B}$ and $C_{\mathcal{A}\mathcal{B}}$ the spin correlation matrix, $\sigma^i$ is the $i$-th Pauli matrix, and repeated indices are summed.
Definition: The average of a quantity $X$ is defined as
\begin{equation}
\langle X\rangle\equiv \frac{1}{(4\pi)^4}\int d \Omega_\mathcal{A} d \Omega_\mathcal{B} d \Omega_\mathcal{C}  d \Omega_\mathcal{D} X \frac{1}{\sigma}\frac{d\sigma}{d \Omega_\mathcal{A} d \Omega_\mathcal{B} d \Omega_\mathcal{C}  d \Omega_\mathcal{D}}.
\end{equation}
Definition: The cross section of production and decay of four qubits $(\mathcal{A,B,C,D})$ is given by
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{\sigma}\frac{d\sigma}{d \Omega_\mathcal{A}d \Omega_\mathcal{B}d \Omega_\mathcal{C}d \Omega_\mathcal{D}} = \frac{1}{(4\pi)^4} \Gamma_{a\bar{a}}^{\mathcal{A}} \Gamma_{b\bar{b}}^{\mathcal{B}}
\Gamma_{c\bar{c}}^{\mathcal{C}}
\Gamma_{d\bar{d}}^{\mathcal{D}}
\rho_{abcd,\bar{a}\bar{b}\bar{c}\bar{d}}, \label{eq:sigma4}
\end{equation}
where the repeated indices are implicitly contracted, $\rho_{abcd,\bar{a}\bar{b}\bar{c}\bar{d}}$ is the density matrix of the system $(\mathcal{A,B,C,D})$, and $\Omega_\mathcal{X}$ is the solid angle directions of the decay product of qubit $\mathcal{X}$, $a\bar{a}$,...,$d\bar{d}$ are the indices of the Pauli matrices. and
\begin{equation}
\hat\Gamma^\mathcal{X}=\frac{\hat{\mathbb{I}}+\kappa_\mathcal{X} \Omega^i_\mathcal{X} \sigma^i}{2},
\end{equation}
where $\kappa_\mathcal{X}$ is a constant.
Definition: Without performing any measurement on the other two particles $(\mathcal{B},\mathcal{C})$, the decay distribution of $(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{D})$ is related to their density matrix $\rho_{ad\bar{a}\bar{d}}$ as
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{\sigma}\frac{d\sigma}{d \Omega_{\mathcal{A}} d \Omega_{\mathcal{D}}} = \frac{1}{(4\pi)^2} \rho_{ad\bar{a}\bar{d}}\Gamma_{a\bar{a}}^{\mathcal{A}} \Gamma_{d\bar{d}}^{\mathcal{D}} .
\end{equation}
This is the pre-measurement distribution.
Definition: After conduct measuring on the system $\mathcal{B,C}$, the post-measurement distribution of decay products of system $\mathcal{A,D}$ is given by
\begin{align}
\frac{1}{\sigma}\frac{d \sigma'}{d \Omega_{\mathcal{A}} d \Omega_{\mathcal{D}}} &= \frac{1}{(4\pi)^4} \int d\Omega_{\mathcal{B}}\Omega_{\mathcal{C}} f(\Omega_{\mathcal{B}},\Omega_{\mathcal{C}}) \Gamma_{a\bar{a}}^{\mathcal{A}} \Gamma_{b\bar{b}}^{\mathcal{B}}
\Gamma_{c\bar{c}}^{\mathcal{C}}
\Gamma_{d\bar{d}}^{\mathcal{D}} \rho_{abcd,\bar{a}\bar{b}\bar{c}\bar{d}} \\
&= \frac{1}{(4\pi)^2} \langle f(\Omega_{\mathcal{B}},\Omega_{\mathcal{C}}) \rangle\rho^{\mathrm{post}}_{ad\bar{a}\bar{d}}\Gamma_{a\bar{a}}^{\mathcal{A}} \Gamma_{d\bar{d}}^{\mathcal{D}}
\end{align}
where $\rho^{\mathrm{post}}_{ad\bar{a}\bar{d}}$ is the post-measurement density martix.

