backgrounds:
Definition (Linear system with a regulator $\epsilon$): Let $\mathbf{f}(x,\epsilon)\in\mathbb{C}^n$ satisfy a first-order system
\begin{align}
\frac{d}{dx}\mathbf{f}(x,\epsilon)=A(x,\epsilon)\,\mathbf{f}(x,\epsilon),
\label{eq:sysf}
\end{align}
where $A$ is a rational matrix in $x$ and (typically) polynomial/rational in $\epsilon$.
Definition (Change of basis / gauge transformation): Let $\mathbf{f}=T(x,\epsilon)\mathbf{g}$ with $T$ invertible. Then $\mathbf{g}$ satisfies
\begin{align}
\frac{d}{dx}\mathbf{g}=A'(x,\epsilon)\mathbf{g},
\qquad
A' = T^{-1}AT - T^{-1}\frac{dT}{dx}.
\label{eq:gaugetrans}
\end{align}
Definition ($\epsilon$-form / canonical form): A system is in $\epsilon$-form if it can be written as
\begin{align}
\frac{d}{dx}\mathbf{g}(x,\epsilon)
=
\epsilon\,\sum_{i} \frac{M_i}{x-a_i}\,\mathbf{g}(x,\epsilon),
\label{eq:epsform}
\end{align}
with constant matrices $M_i$ (independent of $x,\epsilon$). Equivalently, in differential-form notation,
\begin{align}
d\mathbf{g}=\epsilon\, d\tilde A\,\mathbf{g},
\qquad
\tilde A=\sum_i M_i\log(x-a_i).
\label{eq:dform}
\end{align}
This is the “canonical form”: once achieved, the solution is an iterated-integral series in $\epsilon$,
and the letters are just the singular points $\{a_i\}$.
Definition (Iterated-integral expansion): Fix a basepoint $x_0$. Writing $\mathbf{g}(x,\epsilon)=\sum_{k\ge0}\epsilon^k\mathbf{g}^{(k)}(x)$,
the equation in $\epsilon$-form gives the recursion
\begin{align}
\frac{d}{dx}\mathbf{g}^{(0)}(x)=0,\qquad
\frac{d}{dx}\mathbf{g}^{(k)}(x)=\sum_i\frac{M_i}{x-a_i}\,\mathbf{g}^{(k-1)}(x)\quad (k\ge1),
\label{eq:rec}
\end{align}
so $\mathbf{g}^{(k)}$ is a linear combination of weight-$k$ iterated integrals (logs, dilogs, etc.).

